== Metatheory  <syntactic-metatheory>

We can now begin to lay out some of the metatheoretic results that we'll need to develop
an equational theory for #liter. Probably the most important of these is _weakening_, 
which says that, if we can type $a$ as $A$ in a given context, we can freely:

- Add variables (with fresh names) to the context

- Restrict the types of variables $x : X$ to subtypes $x : X'$ where $subty(X', X)$

- Type $a : A'$ for any supertype $subty(A, A')$

Formally, we can state the _(syntactic) weakening lemma_ as follows: 

#lemma("Weakening")[
  If #hasty($őď$, $a$, $A$), #wkns($őď'$, $őď$), and #subty($A$, $A'$),
  then #hasty($őď'$, $a$, $A'$)
  --
  i.e. the following rule is admissible:
  #align(center, prooftree(adm-weakening))
]

In general, we say that a rule like #rle("Wk") is _admissible_ 
if we can prove (e.g. by induction on derivations) that, 
whenever the premises hold, the conclusion is derivable
--
hence, we can soundly use this rule when proving something is derivable.

Nonetheless, a rule being admissible is a weaker condition than a rule being
_derivable_ by simple composition of other rules, e.g., the way @fig-pair-deriv
derives #hasty($őď$, $(a, (b, c))$, $A tytensor (B tytensor C)$) from the
assumptions #hasty($őď$, $a$, $A$), #hasty($őď$, $b$, $B$), and #hasty($őď$, $c$, $C$)
by two applications of #rle[pair]
--
since, while every derivable rule is trivially admissible, not every admissible
rule is derivable.

#figure(
  prooftree(rule(
    label: msc("pair"),
    hasty($őď$, $a$, $A$),
    rule(
      label: msc("pair"),
      hasty($őď$, $b$, $B$),
      hasty($őď$, $c$, $C$),
      hasty($őď$, $(b, c)$, $B tytensor C$),
    ),
    hasty($őď$, $(a, (b, c))$, $A tytensor (B tytensor C)$),
  )),
  caption: [Deriving #hasty($őď$, $(a, (b, c))$, $A tytensor (B tytensor C)$) from
    #hasty($őď$, $a$, $A$), #hasty($őď$, $b$, $B$), and #hasty($őď$, $c$, $C$) by two
    applications of #rle[pair].],
) <fig-pair-deriv>

In particular, if we _extend_ the set of typing rules by adding a new rule,
every derivable rule stays derivable, but admissible rules may stop being admissible
--
for example, adding the #rle[nodeps] rule of @fig-nodeps, which types
#hasty($¬∑$, $ms("nodeps")(a)$, $A$) in the empty context for every closed
#hasty($¬∑$, $a$, $A$), would make weakening false.
Indeed, as @fig-nodeps-wk shows, both premises of #rle[Wk] hold
--
#hasty($¬∑$, $ms("nodeps")(a)$, $A$) is derivable, and $x : A$ weakens the empty
context, #wkns($x : A$, $¬∑$)
--
yet the conclusion #hasty($x : A$, $ms("nodeps")(a)$, $A$) is _not_ derivable,
since #rle[nodeps] requires the empty context, even though the set of derivable
judgements has strictly expanded.

#figure(
  prooftree(rule(
    label: msc("nodeps"),
    hasty($¬∑$, $a$, $A$),
    hasty($¬∑$, $ms("nodeps")(a)$, $A$),
  )),
  caption: [A hypothetical rule #rle[nodeps] typing #ms("nodeps")-terms only in
    the empty context.],
) <fig-nodeps>

#figure(
  prooftree(rule(
    label: msc("Wk"),
    rule(
      label: msc("nodeps"),
      hasty($¬∑$, $a$, $A$),
      hasty($¬∑$, $ms("nodeps")(a)$, $A$),
    ),
    rule(
      label: msc("drop"),
      rule(label: msc("nil"), wkns($¬∑$, $¬∑$)),
      wkns($x : A$, $¬∑$),
    ),
    $cancel(hasty(x : A, ms("nodeps")(a), A))$,
  )),
  caption: [With #rle[nodeps] added, #rle[Wk] is no longer admissible: both
    premises are derivable, yet the struck-through conclusion is not.],
) <fig-nodeps-wk>

Weakening allows us to _transport_ a judgement we've proved in a local context
--
for example, proving an expression is well-typed given the types of the variables appearing in that expression
--
into a broader program context which may, as an example, contain many more variables,
or assign those variables more specific types.

In general, we want to promote _compositional_ reasoning, 
in which we prove properties about a small program
fragment in isolation and then use those to prove properties about the larger program as a whole.

The next piece in the puzzle here is _(syntactic)_ substitution, which states, in essence,
that we can replace a variable $x : A$ with a program fragment $a : A$ and maintain well-typedness.
In particular, we may define _single variable substitution_ $subvar(a, x, b)$ 
--
read "substitute $a$ for $x$ in $b$"
--
by induction as follows:

#figure(
  rule-set(..subst-var-eqns),
  caption: [Definition of single-variable substitution $subvar(a, x, b)$.]
) <fig-expr-subst-def>

We may then state the _substitution lemma_ as follows

#lemma("Single-Variable Substitution")[
  If #hasty($őď$, $a$, $A$) and #hasty($őď, x : A$, $b$, $B$),
  then #hasty($őď$, $subvar(a, x, b)$, $B$)
  --
  i.e., the following rule is admissible:
  #align(center, prooftree(adm-subst))
]

There still remain two important gaps in our syntactic metatheory.
For one, it is easy to see that the typing rules in @fig-expr-typing
don't depend on the _ordering_ of variables in a context $őď$.
In the same spirit, the rules also don't depend on variables having any
particular _name_
--
that is, if $hasty(őď, a, A)$, then we expect
$hasty(subap(ŌĀ, őď), subap(ŌĀ, a), A)$ where $ŌĀ : vars ‚Üí vars$
is an injective _renaming_.

This is quite difficult to state and prove using single-variable substitutions
--
for example, if we want to rename $x$ to $y$ and $y$ to $x$ in the pair $(x, y)$,
we have
$
  subvar(y, x, subvar(x, y, (x, y))) = subvar(y, x, (y, y)) = (x, x)
$
which is obviously not equal to our expected $(y, x)$
--
forcing us in general to introduce temporary fresh variables
$
  subvar(x, t_y, subvar(y, t_x, subvar(y, t_y, subvar(x, t_x, (x, y))))) 
  = subvar(x, t_y, subvar(y, t_x, (t_x, t_y)))
  = (y, x)
$
to obtain the desired result.

In general, it can be a lot more convenient to reason about _simultaneous substitution_

$
  subap(#$x ‚Ü¶ y, y ‚Ü¶ x$, (x, y)) = (y, x)
$

with renaming falling out as the special case where every variable maps to a unique variable.

To do this, we begin by defining a _substitution list_, or just _substitution_, 
as a list $ŌÉ$ of (variable, term) pairs $x ‚Ü¶ a$
--
we can then define _capture-avoiding simultaneous substitution_ as a _partial_ function 
$ms("Subst") ‚Üí ms("Term") ‚Üí ms("Term")$
by induction on terms as follows:

#figure(
  rule-set(..subst-par-eqns),
  caption: [Action $subap(ŌÉ, a)$ of a simultaneous substitution on a term.],
) <fig-expr-subst-act>

We may then define a typing judgement $issub(őď', ŌÉ, őď)$,
read "$ŌÉ$ takes $őď'$ to $őď$",
in @fig-expr-subst as follows:

#figure(
  rule-set(
    prooftree(sub-nil),
    prooftree(sub-cons),
  ),
  caption: [Typing of simultaneous substitutions $issub(őď', ŌÉ, őď)$.],
) <fig-expr-subst>

allowing us to state the _(syntactic, simultaneous) substitution lemma_ as follows:

#lemma("Simultaneous Substitution")[
  If #issub($őď'$, $ŌÉ$, $őď$) and #hasty($őď$, $a$, $A$),
  then #hasty($őď'$, $subap(ŌÉ, a)$, $A$)
  --
  that is, the following rule is admissible:
  #align(center, prooftree(adm-subst-par))
]

