We now want to build an _equational theory_ for #liter
-- that is, a judgement
$
  eqat(őď, a_1, a_2, A)
$
read "in the context $őď$, the terms $a_1$, $a_2$ are _equivalent_ at the type $A$"
--
where we say that $a_1$ and $a_2$ are equivalent if their behaviour is indistinguishable
_when interpreted as values of type $A$_
-- that is, the type $A$ can be viewed as _carrying_ 
the information of what can and cannot be observed about $a_i$.

However, to be able to support optimizations like _common subexpression elimination_,
which in this setting looks like the substitution
$
  eqat(őď, letx(x, a, b), subvar(a, x, b), B)
$
we need to be able to distinguish between _pure_ and _impure_ terms.

In particular, while syntactic substitution means that 
both sides are well-typed given the same preconditions
--
namely, whenever $hasty(őď, a, A)$ and #hasty($őď, x : A$, $b$, $B$).
--
they aren't in general interchangeble, even without taking instructions
into account.

For example, defining the _infinite loop_
$hasty(őď, loopx = iterx((), x, linr(x)), A)$
--
note this is well-typed for arbitrary $A$
--
we have that

$
  neat(őď, 
    letx(x, loopx, subvar(x, x, ())), 
    subvar(loopx, x, ()), 
    ()
  )  
$
since the former diverges while the latter does not.

The typical way that this is handled is by distinguishing 
a _syntactic_ category of _values_ $v ‚ąą vals$, like $3$ or $5$,
and then stating that
$
  eqat(őď, letx(x, v, b), subvar(v, x, b), B)
$
only when we in fact have $v ‚ąą vals$.

The issue with this approach for our purposes is that 
we would like to study _algebraic rewrites_ like
$
  eqat(őď, letx(x, y + y, x + x), 4 * y, ‚Ą§)
$
as well as, eventually, optimizations 
like _global value numbering_ and _common subexpression elimination_
in the context of SSA.

Instead, therefore, we will introduce an _effectful_ variant of our typing judgement,
$
  hastye(őď, őĶ, a, A)
$
with reading "in the context $őď$, the term $a$ has type $A$ and effect _at most_ $őĶ$."

Here, we draw $őĶ$ from an _effect signature_ #effs:

- a _bounded_ lattice
  --
  that is, a partially ordered set #effs
  having a top $‚ä§$, bottom $‚ä•$, 
  meets (infima) $‚äď$, and joins (suprema) $‚äĒ$
  --
  equipped with:

- a _fixpoint operator_ 
  #effiter($őĶ$) which is
  - _extensive_: $‚ąÄ őĶ, őĶ ‚Č§ effiter(őĶ)$
  - _idempotent_: $‚ąÄ őĶ, effiter((effiter(őĶ))) = effiter(őĶ)$
  representing the effect obtained by iterating $őĶ$ 
  an unbounded (potentially infinite) number of times.

  We say an effect is _iterative_ if $effiter(őĶ) = őĶ$
  -- this is true if and only if there exists $őĶ'$ s.t. $effiter(őĶ') = őĶ$.

  We say an effect signature is _complete_ if every effect is iterative.

The most basic example of an effect signature 
is the _boolean effect signature_: 
the boolean lattice ${‚ä•, ‚ä§}$ equipped with $effiter(‚ä•) = effiter(‚ä§) = ‚ä§$.

We will also make use of:

- The _trivial effect signature_ ${‚ä§ = ‚ä• = *}$

- The _complete boolean effect signature_: 
  the boolean lattice ${‚ä•, ‚ä§}$ equipped with $effiter(őĶ) = őĶ$

We can now extend our signature $cal(S)$ with

- An effect signature #effs

- For each instruction $f ‚ąą cal(I)$, 
  an effect #ieff($f$)
  
We then likewise introduce an effectful version $hastye(őď, őĶ, a, A)$
of our typing judgement $hasty(őď, a, A)$
which bounds the effects of $a$ above by $őĶ$.
We give the rules for this judgement in @fig-expr-typing-eff.

#figure(
  rule-set(
    prooftree(te-var),
    prooftree(te-inst),
    prooftree(te-op),
    prooftree(te-let),
    prooftree(te-unit),
    prooftree(te-pair),
    prooftree(te-let-pair),
    prooftree(te-inl),
    prooftree(te-inr),
    prooftree(te-abort),
    prooftree(te-case),
    prooftree(te-iter),
  ),
  caption: [Effectful typing rules for #liter.],
) <fig-expr-typing-eff>

For the most part, these rules are the same as those given @fig-expr-typing,
except that the effect of an expression is determined by the effect of its components.
In particular:

- Pure expressions like variables $x$ and units $()$ can be typed with an _arbitrary_ effect
  $hastye(őď, őĶ, x, A)$ (#rle("var")), $hastye(őď, őĶ, (), mb(1))$ (#rle("unit"))

- An application $f med a$ can be typed with any effect $őĶ$ which types $a$
  such that $ieff(f) ‚Č§ őĶ$ (#rle("inst"), #rle("op"))

- The effect $őĶ$ of an iteration expression $iterx(a, x, b)$ is restricted to be iterative

It is straightforward to derive that
$
  ‚ąÄ őĶ . hastye(őď, őĶ, a, A) ==> hasty(őď, a, A)
$

On the other hand, we note in particular that $‚ä§$ must be iterative, 
since $‚ä§ ‚Č§ effiter(‚ä§) ==> ‚ä§ = effiter(‚ä§)$ by the definition of a top element.
It follows that, since every $ieff(f) ‚Č§ ‚ä§$, we have that

$
  hasty(őď, a, A) ==> hastye(őď, ‚ä§, a, A)
$
and hence, by the above,
$
  
  hasty(őď, a, A) <==> hastye(őď, ‚ä§, a, A)
$

Likewise, we can derive by a straightforward induction that
#hastye($őď$, $őĶ'$, $a$, $A$)
for all $őĶ ‚Č§ őĶ'$
--
in particular, our weakening lemma becomes:

#lemma("Weakening")[
  If #hastye($őĒ$, $őĶ$, $a$, $A$), #wkns($őď$, $őĒ$), #subty($A$, $B$),
  and $őĶ ‚Č§ őĶ'$, then #hastye($őď$, $őĶ'$, $a$, $B$)
  --
  i.e., the following rule is admissible:
  #align(center, prooftree(adm-weakening-eff))
]

Likewise, single-variable substitution replays verbatim:

#lemma("Single-Variable Substitution")[
  If #hastye($őď$, $őĶ$, $a$, $A$) and #hastye($őď, x : A$, $őĶ$, $b$, $B$),
  then #hastye($őď$, $őĶ$, $subvar(a, x, b)$, $B$)
  --
  i.e., the following rule is admissible:
  #align(center, prooftree(adm-subst-eff))
]

To state simultaneous substitution, we can introduce an effectful
typing judgement on substitutions in the straightforward manner,
given in @fig-expr-subst-eff:

#figure(
  rule-set(
    prooftree(sube-nil),
    prooftree(sube-cons),
  ),
  caption: [Effectful typing of simultaneous substitutions #issube($őď$, $őĶ$, $ŌÉ$, $őĒ$).],
) <fig-expr-subst-eff>

Simultaneous substitution then becomes:

#lemma("Simultaneous Substitution")[
